0061|- [HelpText]
0062|*In addition to the general device-dependent control words, the following
0063|*control codes are available for moving and rotating of texts:
0064|- shadow %: [LINK(q111_13.html)] [/LINK]
0065|*(Same specifications are also available in GPLOT, see TEXTROT?)
S   |                                                       %%%%%%%
0067|*  [MOVE(x,y)]    moves the start of the text by x in X direction and by y
0068|*                 in Y direction.
0069|*  [ROT(angle)]   rotates the text by an angle given in degrees.
0071|*The following example illustrates the use of these control words:
0072|*...............
0073|*PLOT Y(X)=10*SIN(X) / DEVICE=PS,TEST.PS
0074|*/GS-PDF TEST.PS
0075|*HEADER=[MOVE(500,-50)][Timesb(18)],Test_plot
0076|*PEN=[MOVE(0,0)][ROT(0)][Swiss(10)]
0077|*YSCALE=[ROT(90)],-10(2)10
0078|*YSCALE2=[MOVE(0,30)][ROT(-90)],-10(2)10
0079|*YSCALEPOS=-50,50
0080|*...............
0081|*                             See [char_width(x)] on the next page!
0083|*When using fonts of proportional pitch (as Times or Swiss), equally
0084|*spaced text can be printed by using [char_width(x)] where x is the
0085|*character width given in Points. [char_width(0)] means resuming the
0086|*normal proportional pitch again.
0087|*This facility is useful in plotting Y scale notations in graphs in order
0088|*to get notations correctly aligned.
0089|*Typical example: PEN=[Swiss(10)][char_width(0)]
0090|*                 YSCALE=[char_width(8)],-4(2)2
0092|- shadow a: [LINK(q0p4_01.html)]
0093|*  P = More information on PostScript plotting
